          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "Over 250000 learners",
          "247 MOOCs from Harvard, MIT and Stanford",
          "LMS logs",
          "Theory of Planned Behavior",
          "[Manually Coded Learning Plans]",
          "Authors do a manual coding process to identify planning tactics: essencially to answer 3 questions when, where and how. \n\nThis was done using a 3 stage plan created from a sample of courses and plans,\n\nLearning tactics were found to be non-collinear using VIF",
          "Linear Regression",
          "Completion\n{Pseudo-RSquared: 0.17 - How Plans}\n\nProgress\n{Pseudo-RSquared: 0.25 - When/Where Plans}",
          "-",
          "The manual coding allowed to creation of multiple features associated with different SRL constructs. ",
          "Time is found to be the only factor positively associated with Course Completion. \n\nStudents who plan to prioritize and make a routine end up exhausting themselves early and dropping out. \n\nBreaking down end-goal into sub-goals is often better and more effective. Course Designers can and should consider this in their course design.\n\nMany individuals do not follow planning instructions.\n\n\n",
          "Authors essencially do a Regression analysis based on 2 distinct feature sets. On the one hand, authors use When/Where plans to evaluate completion or Progress in a MOOC. \n\nOn a second analysis, the authors look at How plans to do the same analysis.",
          "MOOCs considered are mostly from STEM courses.\n\nDubious long-term reliability of results since most planning is done for the short-term.\n\nOnly uses OLS but should consider other options that allow the modelling of co-variate relationships.\n\nDoes not consider the specificity of a plan. "
        ]
      ],
      "index": 7
    }
  ],
